# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: linux-kernel
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:linux-kernel/kernel-preemption] In computer operating system design, **kernel preemption** is a property possessed by some kernels, in which the CPU can be interrupted in the middle of executing kernel code and assigned other tasks (from which it later returns to finish its kernel tasks).
[src:linux-kernel/kernel-preemption] It is used mainly in monolithic and hybrid kernels, where all or most device drivers are run in kernel space.
[src:linux-kernel/kernel-preemption] Linux is an example of a monolithic-kernel operating system with kernel preemption.
[src:linux-kernel/kernel-preemption] The main benefit of kernel preemption is that it solves two issues that would otherwise be problematic for monolithic kernels, in which the kernel consists of one large binary.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] The **Linux kernel** is a free and open-source Unix-like kernel that is used in many computer systems worldwide.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] The kernel was created by Linus Torvalds in 1991 and was soon adopted as the kernel for the GNU operating system (OS), which was created to be a free replacement for Unix.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Since the late 1990s, it has been included in many operating system distributions, many of which are called Linux.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] One such Linux kernel operating system is Android, which is used in many mobile and embedded devices.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Most of the kernel code is written in C as supported by the GNU Compiler Collection (GCC), which has extensions beyond standard C.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] The code also contains assembly code for architecture-specific logic such as optimizing memory use and task execution.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] The kernel has a modular design such that modules can be integrated as software components – including dynamically loaded.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] The kernel is monolithic in an architectural sense since the entire OS kernel runs in kernel space.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Linux is provided under the GNU General Public License version 2, although it contains files under other compatible licenses.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] In 1991, Linus Torvalds was a computer science student enrolled at the University of Helsinki.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] During his time there, he began to develop an operating system as a side-project inspired by UNIX, for a personal computer.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] He started with a task switcher in Intel 80386 assembly language and a terminal driver.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] On 17 September 1991, Torvalds prepared version 0.01 of Linux and put on the "ftp.funet.fi" – FTP server of the Finnish University and Research Network (FUNET).
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] It was not even executable since its code still needed Minix to compile and test it.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] On 5 October 1991, Torvalds announced the first "official" version of Linux, version 0.02.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] At the time, the GNU Project had completed many components for its free UNIX replacement, GNU, but its kernel, the GNU Hurd, was incomplete.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] The project adopted the Linux kernel for its OS.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Torvalds labeled the kernel with major version 0 to indicate that it was not yet intended for general use.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Version 0.11, released in December 1991, was the first version to be self-hosted; compiled on a computer running the Linux kernel.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] When Torvalds released version 0.12 in January 1992, he adopted the GNU General Public License version 2 (GPLv2) over his previous self-drafted license, which had not permitted commercial redistribution.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] In contrast to Unix, all Linux source files are freely available, including device drivers.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] The initial success of Linux was driven by programmers and testers across the world.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Because Linux implemented Unix-like system call semantics and exposed the standard POSIX APIs through an implementation of the C standard library, Linux could run software and applications that had been originally developed for Unix.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] On 19 January 1992, the first post to the new newsgroup *alt.os.linux* was submitted.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] On 31 March 1992, the newsgroup was renamed *comp.os.linux*.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] The fact that Linux is a monolithic kernel rather than a microkernel was the topic of a debate between Andrew S.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Tanenbaum, the creator of MINIX, and Torvalds.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] The Tanenbaum–Torvalds debate started in 1992 on the Usenet group *comp.os.minix* as a general discussion about kernel architectures.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Version 0.96 released in May 1992 was the first capable of running the X Window System.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] In March 1994, Linux 1.0.0 was released with 176,250 lines of code.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] As indicated by the version number, it was the first version considered suitable for a production environment.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] In June 1996, after release 1.3, Torvalds decided that Linux had evolved enough to warrant a new major number, and so labeled the next release as version 2.0.0.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Significant features of 2.0 included symmetric multiprocessing (SMP), support for more processors types and support for selecting specific hardware targets and for enabling architecture-specific features and optimizations.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] The *make *config* family of commands of *kbuild* enable and configure options for building ad hoc kernel executables (vmlinux) and loadable modules.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Version 2.2, released on 20 January 1999, improved locking granularity and SMP management, added m68k, PowerPC, Sparc64, Alpha, and other 64-bit platforms support.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Furthermore, it added new file systems including Microsoft's NTFS read-only capability.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] In 1999, IBM published its patches to the Linux 2.2.13 code for the support of the S/390 architecture.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Version 2.4.0, released on 4 January 2001, contained support for ISA Plug and Play, USB, and PC Cards.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Linux 2.4 added support for the Pentium 4 and Itanium (the latter introduced the ia64 ISA that was jointly developed by Intel and Hewlett-Packard to supersede the older PA-RISC), and for the newer 64-bit MIPS processor.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Development for 2.4.*x* changed a bit in that more features were made available throughout the series, including support for Bluetooth, Logical Volume Manager (LVM) version 1, RAID support, InterMezzo and ext3 file systems.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Version 2.6.0 was released on 17 December 2003.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] The development for 2.6.*x* changed further towards including new features throughout the series.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Starting with 2.6.x releases, the kernel supported a large number of file systems.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Some were designed for Linux, like ext3, ext4, FUSE, and Btrfs.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Others were native to other operating systems like JFS, XFS, Minix, Xenix, Irix, Solaris, System V, Windows, and MS-DOS.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Though development had not used a version control system thus far, in 2002, Linux developers adopted BitKeeper, which was made freely available to them even though it was not free software.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] In 2005, because of efforts to reverse-engineer it, the company that owned the software revoked its support of the Linux community.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] In response, Torvalds and others wrote Git.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] The new system was written within weeks, and in two months the first official kernel made using it was released.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] In 2005 the *stable team* was formed as a response to the lack of a kernel tree where people could work on bug fixes, and it would keep updating *stable* versions.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] In February 2008 the *linux-next* tree was created to serve as a place where patches aimed to be merged during the next development cycle gathered.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Several subsystem maintainers also adopted the suffix *-next* for trees containing code that they mean to submit for inclusion in the next release cycle.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] As of January 2014, the in-development version of Linux is held in an unstable branch named *linux-next*.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] The 20th anniversary of Linux was celebrated by Torvalds in July 2011 with the release of version 3.0.0.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] As 2.6 had been the version number for 8 years, a new *uname26* personality that reports 3.x as 2.6.40+x had to be added to the kernel so that old programs would work.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Version 3.0 was released on 22 July 2011.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] On 30 May 2011, Torvalds announced that the big change was "NOTHING.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Absolutely nothing." and asked, "...let's make sure we really make the next release not just an all new shiny number, but a good kernel too." After the expected 6–7 weeks of the development process, it would be released near the 20th anniversary of Linux.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] The same series unified support for the ARM processor.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] The numbering change from 2.6.39 to 3.0, and from 3.19 to 4.0, involved no meaningful technical differentiation; the major version number was increased simply to avoid large minor numbers.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Stable 3.x.y kernels were released until 3.19 in February 2015.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Version 3.11, released on 2 September 2013, added many new features such as the new O_TMPFILE flag for `open(2)` to reduce temporary file vulnerabilities, experimental AMD Radeon dynamic power management, low-latency network polling, and zswap (compressed swap cache).
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] In April 2015, Torvalds released kernel version 4.0.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] By February 2015, Linux had received contributions from nearly 12,000 programmers from more than 1,200 companies, including some of the world's largest software and hardware vendors.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Version 4.1 of Linux, released in June 2015, contains over 19.5 million lines of code contributed by almost 14,000 programmers.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] A total of 1,991 developers, of whom 334 were first-time collaborators, added more than 553,000 lines of code to version 5.8, breaking the record previously held by version 4.9.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] According to the Stack Overflow's annual Developer Survey of 2019, more than 53% of all respondents have developed software for Linux and about 27% for Android, although only about 25% develop with Linux-based operating systems.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Most websites run on Linux-based operating systems, and all of the world's 500 most powerful supercomputers run on Linux.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Linux distributions bundle the kernel with system software (e.g., the GNU C Library, systemd, and other Unix utilities and daemons) and a wide selection of application software, but their usage share in desktops is low in comparison to other operating systems.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Android, which runs on a modified Linux kernel, accounts for the majority of mobile device operating systems, and is increasingly being used in embedded devices, making it a significant driver of Linux adoption.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] The cost to redevelop version 2.6.0 of the Linux kernel in a traditional proprietary development setting has been estimated to be US$612 million (€467M, £394M) in 2004 prices using the COCOMO person-month estimation model.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] In 2006, a study funded by the European Union put the redevelopment cost of kernel version 2.6.8 higher, at €882M ($1.14bn, £744M).
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] This topic was revisited in October 2008 by Amanda McPherson, Brian Proffitt, and Ron Hale-Evans.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Wheeler's methodology, they estimated redevelopment of the 2.6.25 kernel now costs $1.3bn (part of a total $10.8bn to redevelop Fedora 9).
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Again, Garcia-Garcia and Alonso de Magdaleno from University of Oviedo (Spain) estimate that the value annually added to kernel was about €100M between 2005 and 2007 and €225M in 2008, it would cost also more than €1bn (about $1.4bn as of February 2010) to develop in the European Union.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] As of 7 March 2011, using then-current LOC (lines of code) of a 2.6.x Linux kernel and wage numbers with David A.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Wheeler's calculations it would cost approximately $3bn (about €2.2bn) to redevelop the Linux kernel as it keeps getting bigger.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] An updated calculation as of 26 September 2018, using then-current 20,088,609 LOC (lines of code) for the 4.14.14 Linux kernel and the current US national average programmer salary of $75,506 show that it would cost approximately $14,725,449,000 (£11,191,341,000) to rewrite the existing code.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Most who use Linux do so via a Linux distribution.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Some distributions ship the vanilla or stable kernel.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Several vendors (such as Red Hat and Debian) maintain a customized source tree.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Graph of the sizes of Linux Kernel versions in millions of lines of code.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] The community of Linux kernel developers comprises about 5000–6000 members.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] According to the "2017 State of Linux Kernel Development", a study issued by the Linux Foundation, covering the commits for the releases 4.8 to 4.13, about 1500 developers were contributing from about 200–250 companies on average.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] The top 30 developers contributed a little more than 16% of the code.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] For companies, the top contributors are Intel (13.1%) and Red Hat (7.2%), Linaro (5.6%), IBM (4.1%), the second and fifth places are held by the 'none' (8.2%) and 'unknown' (4.1%) categories.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Prominent Linux kernel developers have been aware of the importance of avoiding conflicts between developers.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] For a long time there was no code of conduct for kernel developers due to opposition by Torvalds.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] A Linux Kernel *Code of Conflict* was introduced on 8 March 2015.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] It was replaced on 16 September 2018 by a new *Code of Conduct* based on the Contributor Covenant.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] This coincided with a public apology by Torvalds and a brief break from kernel development.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] On 30 November 2018, complying with the *Code of Conduct*, Jarkko Sakkinen of Intel sent out patches replacing instances of "fuck" appearing in source code comments with suitable versions focused on the word 'hug'.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Developers who feel treated unfairly can report this to the Linux Foundation Technical Advisory Board.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] In July 2013, the maintainer of the USB 3.0 driver Sage Sharp asked Torvalds to address the abusive commentary in the kernel development community.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] In 2014, Sharp backed out of Linux kernel development, saying that "The focus on technical excellence, in combination with overloaded maintainers, and people with different cultural and social norms, means that Linux kernel maintainers are often blunt, rude, or brutal to get their job done".
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] At the linux.conf.au (LCA) conference in 2018, developers expressed the view that the culture of the community has gotten much better in the past few years.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Daniel Vetter, the maintainer of the Intel drm/i915 graphics kernel driver, commented that the "rather violent language and discussion" in the kernel community has decreased or disappeared.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Laurent Pinchart asked developers for feedback on their experiences with the kernel community at the 2017 Embedded Linux Conference Europe.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] The issues brought up were discussed a few days later at the Maintainers Summit.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Concerns over the lack of consistency in how maintainers responded to patches submitted by developers were echoed by Shuah Khan, the maintainer of the kernel self-test framework.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Torvalds contended that there would never be consistency in the handling of patches because different kernel subsystems have, over time, adopted different development processes.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Therefore, it was agreed upon that each kernel subsystem maintainer would document the rules for patch acceptance.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] The kernel source code, a.k.a. source tree, is managed in the Git version control system – also created by Torvalds.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] As of 2021, the 5.11 release of the Linux kernel had around 30.34 million lines of code.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Roughly 14% of the code is part of the "core," including architecture-specific code, kernel code, and memory management code, while 60% is drivers.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Contributions are submitted as patches, in the form of text messages on the Linux kernel mailing list (LKML) (and often also on other mailing lists dedicated to particular subsystems).
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] The patches must conform to a set of rules and to a formal language that, among other things, describes which lines of code are to be deleted and what others are to be added to the specified files.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] These patches can be automatically processed so that system administrators can apply them in order to make just some changes to the code or to incrementally upgrade to the next version.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Linux is distributed also in GNU zip (gzip) and bzip2 formats.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] A developer who wants to change the Linux kernel writes and tests a code change.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Depending on how significant the change is and how many subsystems it modifies, the change will either be submitted as a single patch or in multiple patches of source code.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] In case of a single subsystem that is maintained by a single maintainer, these patches are sent as e-mails to the maintainer of the subsystem with the appropriate mailing list in Cc.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] The maintainer and the readers of the mailing list will review the patches and provide feedback.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Once the review process has finished the subsystem maintainer accepts the patches in the relevant Git kernel tree.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] If the changes to the Linux kernel are bug fixes that are considered important enough, a pull request for the patches will be sent to Torvalds within a few days.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Otherwise, a pull request will be sent to Torvalds during the next merge window.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] The merge window usually lasts two weeks and starts immediately after the release of the previous kernel version.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] The Git kernel source tree names all developers who have contributed to the Linux kernel in the *Credits* directory and all subsystem maintainers are listed in *Maintainers*.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] As with many large open-source software projects, developers are required to adhere to the Contributor Covenant, a code of conduct intended to address harassment of minority contributors.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Additionally, to prevent offense the use of inclusive terminology within the source code is mandated.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Linux is written in a special C programming language supported by GCC, a compiler that extends the C standard in many ways, for example using inline sections of code written in the assembly language (in GCC's "AT&T-style" syntax) of the target architecture.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Initial support for the Rust programming language was added in Linux 6.1, which was released in December 2022, with later kernel versions, such as Linux 6.2 and Linux 6.3, further improving the support.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] As for most software, the kernel is versioned as a series of dot-separated numbers.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] For early versions, the version consisted of three or four dot-separated numbers called *major release*, *minor release* and *revision.* At that time, odd-numbered minor releases were for development and testing, while even numbered minor releases for production.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] The optional fourth digit indicated a patch level.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Development releases were indicated with a release candidate suffix (*-rc*).
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] The current versioning conventions are different.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] The odd/even number implying dev/prod has been dropped, and a major version is indicated by the first two numbers together.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] While the time-frame is open for the development of the next major, the -rcN suffix is used to identify the n'th release candidate for the next version.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] For example, the release of the version 4.16 was preceded by seven 4.16-rcN (from -rc1 to -rc7).
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Once a stable version is released, its maintenance is passed to the *stable team*.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Updates to a stable release are identified by a three-number scheme (e.g., 4.16.1, 4.16.2, ...).
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] The kernel is usually built with the GNU toolchain.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] The GNU C compiler, GNU cc, part of the GNU Compiler Collection (GCC), is the default compiler for mainline Linux.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] The GNU Assembler (often called GAS or GNU as) outputs the object files from the GCC generated assembly code.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Finally, the GNU Linker (GNU ld) produces a statically linked executable kernel file called vmlinux.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Both as and ld are part of GNU Binary Utilities (binutils).
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] GNU cc was for a long time the only compiler capable of correctly building Linux.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] In 2004, Intel claimed to have modified the kernel so that its C compiler was also capable of compiling it.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] There was another such reported success in 2009, with a modified 2.6.22 version.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Support for the Intel compiler has been dropped in 2023.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Since 2010, effort has been underway to build Linux with Clang, an alternative compiler for the C language; as of 12 April 2014, the official kernel could almost be compiled by Clang.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] The project dedicated to this effort is named *LLVMLinux* after the LLVM compiler infrastructure upon which Clang is built.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] LLVMLinux does not aim to fork either Linux or the LLVM, therefore it is a meta-project composed of patches that are eventually submitted to the upstream projects.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] By enabling Linux to be compiled by Clang, developers may benefit from shorter compilation times.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] In 2017, developers completed upstreaming patches to support building the Linux kernel with Clang in the 4.15 release, having backported support for X86-64 and AArch64 to the 4.4, 4.9, and 4.14 branches of the stable kernel tree.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Google's Pixel 2 shipped with the first Clang built Linux kernel, though patches for Pixel (1st generation) did exist.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] 2018 saw ChromeOS move to building kernels with Clang by default, while Android made Clang and LLVM's linker LLD required for kernel builds in 2019.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Google moved its production kernel used throughout its datacenters to being built with Clang in 2020.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] The *ClangBuiltLinux* group coordinates fixes to both Linux and LLVM to ensure compatibility, both composed of members from *LLVMLinux* and having upstreamed patches from *LLVMLinux*.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] As with any software, problems with the Linux kernel can be difficult to troubleshoot.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Common challenges relate to userspace vs. kernel space access, misuse of synchronization primitives, and incorrect hardware management.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] An oops is a non-fatal error in the kernel.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] After such an error, operations continue with suspect reliability.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] A panic (generated by panic()) is a fatal error.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] After such an error, the kernel prints a message and halts the computer.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] The kernel provides for *debugging by printing* via printk(), which stores messages in a circular buffer (overwriting older entries with newer).
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] The syslog(2) system call provides for reading and clearing the message buffer and for setting the maximum *log level* of the messages to be sent to the console.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Kernel messages are also exported to userland through the */dev/kmsg* interface.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] The *ftrace* mechanism allow for debugging by tracing.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] It is used for monitoring and debugging Linux at runtime and it can analyze user space latencies due to kernel misbehavior.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Furthermore, *ftrace* allows users to trace Linux at boot-time.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] With KGDB Linux can be debugged in much the same way as userspace programs.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] KGDB requires an additional machine that runs GDB and that is connected to the target to be debugged using a serial cable or Ethernet.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] The Linux kernel project integrates new code on a rolling basis.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Standard operating procedure is that software checked into the project must work and compile without error.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Each kernel subsystem is assigned a maintainer who is responsible for reviewing patches against the kernel code standards and keeping a queue of patches that can be submitted to Torvalds within a merge window that is usually several weeks.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Patches are merged by Torvalds into the source code of the prior stable Linux kernel release, creating the release candidate (-rc) for the next stable release.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Once the merge window is closed, only fixes to the new code in the development release are accepted.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] The -rc development release of the kernel goes through regression testing and once it is considered stable by Torvalds and the subsystem maintainers, a new version is released and the development process starts over again.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] The Git tree that contains the Linux kernel source code is referred to as **mainline Linux**.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Every stable kernel release originates from the mainline tree, and is frequently published on kernel.org.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Mainline Linux has only solid support for a small subset of the many devices that run Linux.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Non-mainline support is provided by independent projects, such as Yocto or Linaro, but in many cases the kernel from the device vendor is needed.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Using a vendor kernel likely requires a board support package.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Maintaining a kernel tree outside of mainline Linux has proven to be difficult.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] The maintainer of the stable branch, Greg Kroah-Hartman, has applied the term *Linux-like* to downstream kernel forks by vendors that add millions of lines of code to the mainline kernel.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] In 2019, Google stated that it wanted to use the mainline Linux kernel in Android so the number of kernel forks would be reduced.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] The term Linux-like has also been applied to the Embeddable Linux Kernel Subset, which does not include the full mainline Linux kernel but a small modified subset of the code.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] There are certain communities that develop kernels based on the official Linux.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Some interesting bits of code from these forks that include Linux-libre, Compute Node Linux, INK, L4Linux, RTLinux, and User-Mode Linux (UML) have been merged into the mainline.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Some operating systems developed for mobile phones initially used heavily modified versions of Linux, including Google Android, Firefox OS, HP webOS, Nokia Maemo and Jolla Sailfish OS.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Today Android uses a customized Linux where major changes are implemented in device drivers, but some changes to the core kernel code is required.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Android developers also submit patches to the official Linux that finally can boot the Android operating system.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] For example, a Nexus 7 can boot and run the mainline Linux.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] The latest version and older versions are maintained separately.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Most of the latest kernel releases were supervised by Torvalds.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] The Linux kernel developer community maintains a stable kernel by applying fixes for software bugs that have been discovered during the development of the subsequent stable kernel.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Therefore, www.kernel.org always lists two stable kernels.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] The next stable Linux kernel is released about 8 to 12 weeks later.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Some releases are designated for long-term support as *longterm* with bug fix releases for two or more years.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] Some projects have attempted to reduce the size of the Linux kernel.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p01] In 2014, Josh Triplett started the -tiny source tree for a reduced size version.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Even though seemingly contradictory, the Linux kernel is both monolithic and modular.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel is classified as a monolithic kernel architecturally since the entire OS runs in kernel space.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] The design is modular since it can be assembled from modules that in some cases are loaded and unloaded at runtime.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] It supports features once only available in closed source kernels of non-free operating systems.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] The rest of the article makes use of the UNIX and Unix-like operating systems convention of the manual pages.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] The number that follows the name of a command, interface, or other feature specifies the section (i.e. the type of the OS' component or feature) it belongs to.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] For example execve(2) refers to a system call, and exec(3) refers to a userspace library wrapper.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] The following is an overview of architectural design and of noteworthy features.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Most device drivers and kernel extensions run in kernel space (ring 0 in many CPU architectures), with full access to the hardware.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Some exceptions run in user space; notable examples are filesystems based on FUSE/CUSE, and parts of UIO.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Furthermore, the X Window System and Wayland, the windowing system and display server protocols that most people use with Linux, do not run within the kernel.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Differently, the actual interfacing with GPUs of graphics cards is an in-kernel subsystem called Direct Rendering Manager (DRM).
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Unlike standard monolithic kernels, device drivers are easily configured as modules, and loaded or unloaded while the system is running and can also be pre-empted under certain conditions in order to handle hardware interrupts correctly and to better support symmetric multiprocessing.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] By choice, Linux has no stable device driver application binary interface.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Linux typically makes use of memory protection and virtual memory and can also handle non-uniform memory access, the project has absorbed μClinux, which also makes it possible to run Linux on microcontrollers without virtual memory.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] The hardware is represented in the file hierarchy.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] User applications interact with device drivers via entries in the /dev or /sys directories.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Process information is mapped into the /proc directory.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Linux started as a clone of UNIX, and aims toward POSIX and Single UNIX Specification compliance.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel provides system calls and other interfaces that are Linux-specific.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] In order to be included in the official kernel, the code must comply with a set of licensing rules.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] The Linux application binary interface (ABI) between the kernel and the user space has four degrees of stability (stable, testing, obsolete, removed); The system calls are expected to never change in order to preserve compatibility for userspace programs that rely on them.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Loadable kernel modules (LKMs), by design, cannot rely on a stable ABI.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Therefore, they must always be recompiled whenever a new kernel executable is installed in a system, otherwise they will not be loaded.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] In-tree drivers that are configured to become an integral part of the kernel executable (vmlinux) are statically linked by the build process.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] There is no guarantee of stability of source-level in-kernel API and, because of this, device driver code, as well as the code of any other kernel subsystem, must be kept updated with kernel evolution.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Any developer who makes an API change is required to fix any code that breaks as the result of their change.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] The set of the Linux kernel API that regards the interfaces exposed to user applications is fundamentally composed of UNIX and Linux-specific system calls.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] A system call is an entry point into the Linux kernel.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] For example, among the Linux-specific ones there is the family of the clone(2) system calls.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Most extensions must be enabled by defining the `_GNU_SOURCE` macro in a header file or when the user-land code is being compiled.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] System calls can only be invoked via assembly instructions that enable the transition from unprivileged user space to privileged kernel space in ring 0.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] For this reason, the C standard library (libC) acts as a wrapper to most Linux system calls, by exposing C functions that, if needed, transparently enter the kernel, which will execute on behalf of the calling process.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] For system calls not exposed by libC, such as the fast userspace mutex, the library provides a function called syscall(2), which can be used to explicitly invoke them.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Pseudo filesystems (e.g., the sysfs and procfs filesystems) and special files (e.g., `/dev/random`, `/dev/sda`, `/dev/tty`, and many others) constitute another layer of interface to kernel data structures representing hardware or logical (software) devices.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] This issue is mainly due to distribution-specific configurations and a set of patches applied to the code of the Linux kernel, differences in system libraries, services (daemons), filesystem hierarchies, and environment variables.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] The main standard concerning application and binary compatibility of Linux distributions is the Linux Standard Base (LSB).
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] The LSB goes beyond what concerns the Linux kernel, because it also defines the desktop specifications, the X libraries and Qt that have little to do with it.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] The LSB version 5 is built upon several standards and drafts (POSIX, SUS, X/Open, File System Hierarchy (FHS), and others).
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] The standard ABI for how x86_64 user programs invoke system calls is to load the syscall number into the *rax* register, and the other parameters into *rdi*, *rsi*, *rdx*, *r10*, *r8*, and *r9*, and finally to put the *syscall* assembly instruction in the code.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] There are several internal kernel APIs between kernel subsystems.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] The Linux developers chose not to maintain a stable in-kernel ABI.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Modules compiled for a specific version of the kernel cannot be loaded into another version without being recompiled.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Linux, as other kernels, has the ability to manage processes including creating, suspending, resuming and terminating.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Unlike other operating systems, the Linux kernel implements processes as a group of threads called tasks.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] If two tasks share the same TGID, then they are called in the kernel terminology a task group.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Each task is represented by a *task_struct* data structure.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] A new process can be created by calling clone family of system calls or fork system call.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Processes can be suspended and resumed by the kernel by sending signals like SIGSTOP and SIGCONT.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] A process can terminate itself by calling exit system call, or terminated by another process by sending signals like SIGKILL, SIGABRT or SIGINT.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] If the executable is dynamically linked to shared libraries, a dynamic linker is used to find and load the needed objects, prepare the program to run and then run it.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] The Native POSIX Thread Library (NPTL) provides the POSIX standard thread interface (*pthreads*) to userspace.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel isn't aware of processes nor threads but it is aware of *tasks*, thus threads are implemented in userspace.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Threads in Linux are implemented as *tasks* sharing resources, while if they aren't sharing called to be independent processes.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel provides the futex(7) (fast user-space mutex) mechanisms for user-space locking and synchronization.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] The majority of the operations are performed in userspace but it may be necessary to communicate with the kernel using the futex(2) system call.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] As opposed to userspace threads described above, *kernel threads* run in kernel space.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] They are threads created by the kernel itself for specialized tasks; they are privileged like the kernel and aren't bound to any process or application.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] The Linux process scheduler is modular, in the sense that it enables different scheduling classes and policies.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Scheduler classes are pluggable scheduler algorithms that can be registered with the base scheduler code.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Each class schedules different types of processes.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] The core code of the scheduler iterates over each class in order of priority and chooses the highest priority scheduler that has a schedulable entity of type struct sched_entity ready to run.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Entities may be threads, group of threads, and even all the processes of a specific user.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Linux provides both user preemption as well as (selectable, up to) full kernel preemption.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Preemption reduces latency, increases responsiveness, and makes Linux more suitable for desktop and real-time applications.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] This comes at a cost of throughput, as work being interrupted worsens cache behavior.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] For normal tasks, by default, the kernel uses the Completely Fair Scheduler (CFS) class, introduced in version 2.6.23.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] The scheduler is defined as a macro in a C header as `SCHED_NORMAL`.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] In other POSIX kernels, a similar policy known as `SCHED_OTHER` allocates CPU timeslices (i.e, it assigns absolute slices of the processor time depending on either predetermined or dynamically computed priority of each process).
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] With user preemption, the kernel scheduler can replace the current process with the execution of a context switch to a different one that therefore acquires the computing resources for running (CPU, memory, and more).
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] With kernel preemption, the kernel can preempt itself when an interrupt handler returns, when kernel tasks block, and whenever a subsystem explicitly calls the schedule() function.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel also contains two POSIX-compliant real-time scheduling classes named `SCHED_FIFO` (realtime first-in-first-out) and `SCHED_RR` (realtime round-robin), both of which take precedence over the default class.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] An additional scheduling policy known as `SCHED_DEADLINE`, implementing the earliest deadline first algorithm (EDF), was added in kernel version 3.14, released on 30 March 2014.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] `SCHED_DEADLINE` takes precedence over all the other scheduling classes.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] In 2023, Peter Zijlstra proposed replacing CFS with an earliest eligible virtual deadline first scheduling (EEVDF) scheduler, to prevent the need for CFS "latency nice" patches.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] The EEVDF scheduler replaced CFS in version 6.6 of the Linux kernel.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel has different causes of concurrency (e.g., interrupts, bottom halves, preemption of kernel and users tasks, symmetrical multiprocessing).
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] They consist of atomic types (which can only be manipulated by a set of specific operators), spinlocks, semaphores, mutexes, and lockless algorithms (e.g., RCUs).
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Most lock-less algorithms are built on top of memory barriers for the purpose of enforcing memory ordering and prevent undesired side effects due to compiler optimization.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] PREEMPT_RT code included in mainline Linux provide *RT-mutexes*, a special kind of Mutex that do not disable preemption and have support for priority inheritance.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Almost all locks are changed into sleeping locks when using configuration for realtime operation.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Priority inheritance avoids priority inversion by granting a low-priority task that holds a contended lock the priority of a higher-priority waiter until that lock is released.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Linux includes a kernel lock validator called *Lockdep*.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Although the management of interrupts could be seen as a single job, it is divided into two.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] This split in two is due to the different time constraints and to the synchronization needs of the tasks whose the management is composed of.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] The first part is made up of an asynchronous interrupt service routine (ISR) that in Linux is known as the *top half*, while the second part is carried out by one of three types of the so-called *bottom halves* (*softirq*, *tasklets,* and *work queues*).
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Linux interrupt service routines can be nested.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] A new IRQ can trap into a high priority ISR that preempts any other lower priority ISR.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] The Linux kernel manages both physical and virtual memory.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] It divides physical memory into zones, each of which has a specific purpose.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Those zones are the most common, but others exist.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Linux implements virtual memory with 4 or 5-level page tables.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel is not pageable (meaning it is always resident in physical memory and cannot be swapped to the disk) and there is no memory protection (no SIGSEGV signals, unlike in user space), therefore memory violations lead to instability and system crashes.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] User memory is pageable by default, although paging for specific memory areas can be disabled with the `mlock()` system call family.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Page frame information is maintained in apposite data structures (of type `struct page`) that are populated immediately after boot and kept until shutdown, regardless of whether they are associated with virtual pages.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] The physical address space is divided into different zones, according to architectural constraints and intended use.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] NUMA systems with multiple memory banks are also supported.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Small chunks of memory can be dynamically allocated in kernel space via the family of `kmalloc()` APIs and freed with the appropriate variant of `kfree()`.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] `vmalloc()` and `kvfree()` are used for large virtually contiguous chunks.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] `alloc_pages()` allocates the desired number of entire pages.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel used to include the SLAB, SLUB and SLOB allocators as configurable alternatives.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] The SLOB allocator was removed in Linux 6.4 and the SLAB allocator was removed in Linux 6.8.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] The sole remaining allocator is SLUB, which aims for simplicity and efficiency, is PREEMPT_RT compatible and was introduced in Linux 2.6.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Since Linux supports numerous filesystems with different features and functionality, it is necessary to implement a generic filesystem that is independent from underlying filesystems.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] The virtual file system interfaces with other Linux subsystems, userspace, or APIs and abstracts away the different implementations of underlying filesystems.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] VFS implements system calls like `create`, `open`, `read`, `write` and `close`.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] VFS implements a generic superblock and inode block that is independent from the one that the underlying filesystem has.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] In this subsystem directories and files are represented by a `struct file` data structure.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] When userspace requests access to a file it is returned a file descriptor (non negative integer value) but in kernel space it is a `struct file` structure.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] This structure stores all the information the kernel knows about a file or directory.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] sysfs and procfs are virtual filesystems that expose hardware information and userspace programs' runtime information.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] These filesystems aren't present on disk and instead the kernel implements them as a callback or routine that gets called when they are accessed by userspace.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] While not originally designed to be portable, Linux is now one of the most widely ported operating system kernels, running on a diverse range of systems from the ARM architecture to IBM z/Architecture mainframe computers.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] The first port was performed on the Motorola 68000 platform.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] The modifications to the kernel were so fundamental that Torvalds viewed the Motorola version as a fork and a "Linux-like operating system".
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] That moved Torvalds to lead a major restructure of the code to facilitate porting to more computing architectures.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] The first Linux that, in a single source tree, had code for more than i386 alone, supported the DEC Alpha AXP 64-bit platform.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Linux is used as the primary operating system on IBM’s Summit supercomputer.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] In October 2019, all systems on the TOP500 list of the world’s fastest supercomputers ran operating systems based on the Linux kernel, whereas the first Linux-based supercomputer appeared on the list in 1998.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Linux has also been ported to various handheld devices such as iPhone 3G and iPod.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] In 2007, the LKDDb project has been started to build a comprehensive database of hardware and protocols known by Linux kernels.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] The database is built automatically by static analysis of the kernel sources.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Later in 2014, the Linux Hardware project was launched to automatically collect a database of all tested hardware configurations with the help of users of various Linux distributions.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Kernel updates can be applied without rebooting by using live patching technologies such as Ksplice, kpatch and kGraft.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Initial support for live kernel patching was merged into the Linux kernel mainline in version 4.0, released on 12 April 2015.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] The feature, known as *livepatch*, uses the kernel's ftrace functionality and provides a common infrastructure for hot patches supplied through kernel modules, together with interfaces for userspace management tools.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] In its initial Linux 4.0 implementation, livepatch support was limited to the x86 architecture and provided basic infrastructure rather than a complete live-patching consistency model.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Kernel bugs present potential security issues.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] For example, they may allow for privilege escalation or create denial-of-service attack vectors.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Over the years, numerous bugs affecting system security were found and fixed.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] New features are frequently implemented to improve the kernel's security.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Capabilities(7) have already been introduced in the section about the processes and threads.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Android makes use of them and systemd gives administrators detailed control over the capabilities of processes.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Linux offers a wealth of mechanisms to reduce kernel attack surface and improve security that are collectively known as the Linux Security Modules (LSM).
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] They comprise the Security-Enhanced Linux (SELinux) module, whose code has been originally developed and then released to the public by the NSA, and AppArmor among others.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] SELinux is now actively developed and maintained on GitHub.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] SELinux and AppArmor provide support to access control security policies, including mandatory access control (MAC), though they profoundly differ in complexity and scope.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Another security feature is the Seccomp BPF (SECure COMPuting with Berkeley Packet Filters), which works by filtering parameters and reducing the set of system calls available to user-land applications.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Linux distributions typically release security updates to fix vulnerabilities in the Linux kernel.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Many offer long-term support releases that receive security updates for a certain Linux kernel version for an extended period of time.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] In 2024, researchers disclosed that the Linux kernel contained a serious vulnerability, CVE-2024-50264, located in the AF_VSOCK subsystem.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] This bug is a use-after-free flaw, a class of memory corruption issue that occurs when a program continues to use memory after it has been freed.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Such flaws are particularly dangerous in the kernel, as they can allow attackers to escalate privileges.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Initially, Torvalds released Linux under a license that forbade any commercial use.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] This was changed in version 0.12 by a switch to the GNU General Public License version 2 (GPLv2).
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] This license allows distribution and sale of possibly modified and unmodified versions of Linux but requires that all those copies be released under the same license and be accompanied by - or that, on request, free access is given to - the complete corresponding source code.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Torvalds has described licensing Linux under the GPLv2 as the "best thing I ever did".
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] The Linux kernel is licensed explicitly under GNU General Public License version 2 only (GPL-2.0-only) with an explicit syscall exception (Linux-syscall-note), without offering the licensee the option to choose any later version, which is a common GPL extension.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Contributed code must be available under GPL-compatible license.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] There was considerable debate about how easily the license could be changed to use later GPL versions (including version 3), and whether this change is even desirable.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Torvalds himself specifically indicated upon the release of version 2.4.0 that his own code is released only under version 2.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] The terms of the GPL state that if no version is specified, then any version may be used, and Alan Cox pointed out that very few other Linux contributors had specified a particular version of the GPL.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] In September 2006, a survey of 29 key kernel programmers indicated that 28 preferred GPLv2 to the then-current GPLv3 draft.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] They referred to clauses regarding DRM/tivoization, patents, "additional restrictions" and warned a Balkanisation of the "Open Source Universe" by the GPLv3.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Torvalds, who decided not to adopt the GPLv3 for the Linux kernel, reiterated his criticism even years later.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] It is debated whether some loadable kernel modules (LKMs) are to be considered derivative works under copyright law, and thereby whether or not they fall under the terms of the GPL.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] In accordance with the license rules, LKMs using only a public subset of the kernel interfaces are non-derived works, thus Linux gives system administrators the mechanisms to load out-of-tree binary objects into the kernel address space.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] There are some out-of-tree loadable modules that make legitimate use of the *dma_buf* kernel feature.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] GPL compliant code can certainly use it.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] A different possible use case would be Nvidia Optimus that pairs a fast GPU with an Intel integrated GPU, where the Nvidia GPU writes into the Intel framebuffer when it is active.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] But, Nvidia cannot use this infrastructure because it necessitates bypassing a rule that can only be used by LKMs that are also GPL.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Alan Cox replied on LKML, rejecting a request from one of Nvidia's engineers to remove this technical enforcement from the API.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Torvalds clearly stated on the LKML that "[I] claim that binary-only kernel modules ARE derivative "by default"'".
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] On the other hand, Torvalds has also said that "[one] gray area in particular is something like a driver that was originally written for another operating system (i.e., clearly not a derived work of Linux in origin).
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] THAT is a gray area, and _that_ is the area where I personally believe that some modules may be considered to not be derived works simply because they weren't designed for Linux and don't depend on any special Linux behaviour".
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Proprietary graphics drivers, in particular, are heavily discussed.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Whenever proprietary modules are loaded into Linux, the kernel marks itself as being "tainted", and therefore bug reports from tainted kernels will often be ignored by developers.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] The official kernel, that is, Torvalds's git branch at the kernel.org repository, contains binary blobs released under the terms of the GNU GPLv2 license.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Linux can also load binary blobs, proprietary firmware, drivers, or other executable modules from the filesystem, and link them into kernel space.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Linux is a registered trademark of Linus Torvalds in the United States, the European Union, and some other countries.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] A legal battle over the trademark began in 1996, when William Della Croce, a lawyer who was never involved in the development of Linux, started requesting licensing fees for the use of the word *Linux*.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] After it was proven that the word was in common use long before Della Croce's claimed first use, the trademark was awarded to Torvalds.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] In October 2024, during the Russian invasion of Ukraine, kernel developer Greg Kroah-Hartman removed some kernel developers whose email addresses suggested a connection to Russia from their roles as maintainers.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] Linus Torvalds responded that he did not support Russian aggression and would not revert the patch, insinuating that opponents of the patch were Russian trolls.
[src:linux-kernel/linux-kernel-p02] James Bottomley, a kernel developer, issued an apology for the handling of the situation and clarified that the action was a consequence of U.S. sanctions against Russia.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] A **loadable kernel module** (**LKM**) is an executable library that extends the capabilities of a running kernel, or so-called *base kernel*, of an operating system.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] LKMs are typically used to add support for new hardware (as device drivers) and/or filesystems, or for adding system calls.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] When the functionality provided by an LKM is no longer required, it can be unloaded in order to free memory and other resources.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] They are also known as **kernel loadable module** (KLM), or simply as **kernel module** (KMOD).
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] Without loadable kernel modules, an operating system would have to include all possible anticipated functionality compiled directly into the base kernel.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] Much of that functionality would reside in memory without being used, wasting memory , and would require that users rebuild and reboot the base kernel every time they require new functionality.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] One minor criticism of preferring a modular kernel over a static kernel is the so-called *fragmentation penalty*.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] The base kernel is always unpacked into real contiguous memory by its setup routines; thus, the base kernel code is never fragmented.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] Loadable kernel modules in Linux are loaded (and unloaded) by the `modprobe` command.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] They are located in `/lib/modules` or `/usr/lib/modules` and have had the extension `.ko` ("kernel object") since version 2.6 (previous versions used the `.o` extension).
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] The `lsmod` command lists the loaded kernel modules.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] In emergency cases, when the system fails to boot due to e.g. broken modules, specific modules can be enabled or disabled by modifying the kernel boot parameters list (for example, if using GRUB, by pressing 'e' in the GRUB start menu, then editing the kernel parameter line).
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] In the opinion of Linux maintainers, LKM are derived works of the kernel.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] The Linux maintainers tolerate the distribution of proprietary modules (such as NVIDIA GPU drivers), but allow only GNU General Public License (GPL) modules to merge to kernel tree of mainline Linux kernel.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] Loading a proprietary or non-GPL-compatible module will set a 'taint' flag in the running kernel—meaning that any problems or bugs experienced will be less likely to be investigated by the maintainers.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] LKMs effectively become part of the running kernel, so can corrupt kernel data structures and produce bugs that may not be able to be investigated if the module is indeed proprietary.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] The string comparison code used by the kernel at the time tried to determine whether the module was GPLed stopped when it reached a null character (`\0`), so it was fooled into thinking that the module was declaring its license to be just "GPL".
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] Kernel modules for FreeBSD are stored within `/boot/kernel/` for modules distributed with the operating system, or usually `/boot/modules/` for modules installed from FreeBSD ports or FreeBSD packages, or for proprietary or otherwise binary-only modules.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] FreeBSD kernel modules usually have the extension `.ko`.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] Once the machine has booted, they may be loaded with the `kldload` command, unloaded with `kldunload`, and listed with `kldstat`.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] Modules can also be loaded from the loader before the kernel starts, either automatically (through `/boot/loader.conf`) or by hand.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] Some loadable kernel modules in macOS can be loaded automatically.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] Loadable kernel modules can also be loaded by the `kextload` command.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] They can be listed by the `kextstat` command.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] Loadable kernel modules are located in bundles with the extension `.kext`.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] Modules supplied with the operating system are stored in the `/System/Library/Extensions` directory; modules supplied by third parties are in various other directories.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] A NetWare kernel module is referred to as a NetWare Loadable Module (NLM).
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] NLMs are inserted into the NetWare kernel by means of the LOAD command, and removed by means of the UNLOAD command; the `modules` command lists currently loaded kernel modules.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] NLMs may reside in any valid search path assigned on the NetWare server, and they have `.NLM` as the file name extension.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] A downloadable kernel module (DKM) type project can be created to generate a ".out" file which can then be loaded to kernel space using "ld" command.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] This downloadable kernel module can be unloaded using "unld" command.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] Solaris has a configurable kernel module load path, which defaults to `/platform/platform-name/kernel /kernel /usr/kernel`.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] Most kernel modules live in subdirectories under `/kernel`; those not considered necessary to boot the system to the point that init can start are often (but not always) found in `/usr/kernel`.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] When running a DEBUG kernel build the system actively attempts to unload modules.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] Linux does not provide a stable API or ABI for kernel modules.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] This means that there are differences in internal structure and function between different kernel versions, which can cause compatibility problems.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] In an attempt to combat those problems, symbol versioning data is placed within the `.modinfo` section of loadable ELF modules.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] This versioning information can be compared with that of the running kernel before loading a module; if the versions are incompatible, the module will not be loaded.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] Other operating systems, such as Solaris, FreeBSD, macOS, and Windows keep the kernel API and ABI relatively stable, thus avoiding this problem.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] For example, FreeBSD kernel modules compiled against kernel version 6.0 will work without recompilation on any other FreeBSD 6.x version, e.g.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] However, they are not compatible with other major versions and must be recompiled for use with FreeBSD 7.x, as API and ABI compatibility is maintained only within a branch.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] While loadable kernel modules are a convenient method of modifying the running kernel, this can be abused by attackers on a compromised system to prevent detection of their processes or files, allowing them to maintain control over the system.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] Many rootkits make use of LKMs in this way.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] Note that, on most operating systems, modules do not help privilege elevation in any way, as elevated privilege is required to load a LKM; they merely make it easier for the attacker to hide the break-in.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] Linux allows disabling module loading via sysctl option `/proc/sys/kernel/modules_disabled`.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] An initramfs system may load specific modules needed for a machine at boot and then disable module loading.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] This makes the security very similar to a monolithic kernel.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] If an attacker can change the initramfs, they can change the kernel binary.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] In OS X Yosemite and later releases, a kernel extension has to be code-signed with a developer certificate that holds a particular "entitlement." Such a developer certificate is only provided by Apple on request and not automatically given to Apple Developer members.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] This feature, called "kext signing", is enabled by default and it instructs the kernel to stop booting if unsigned kernel extensions are present.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] In OS X El Capitan and later releases, it is part of System Integrity Protection.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] In older versions of macOS, or if kext signing is disabled, a loadable kernel module in a kernel extension bundle can be loaded by non-root users if the OSBundleAllowUserLoad property is set to True in the bundle's property list.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] However, if any of the files in the bundle, including the executable code file, are not owned by root and group wheel, or are writable by the group or "other", the attempt to load the kernel loadable module will fail.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] Kernel modules can optionally have a cryptographic signature ELF section which is verified on load depending on the Verified Boot policy settings.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] The kernel can enforce that modules are cryptographically signed by a set of trusted certificates; the list of trusted certificates is held outside of the OS in the ILOM on some SPARC based platforms.
[src:linux-kernel/loadable-kernel-module] Userspace initiated kernel module loading is only possible from the Trusted Path when the system is running with the Immutable Global Zone feature enabled.
[src:linux-kernel/monolithic-kernel] A **monolithic kernel** is an operating system architecture with the entire operating system running in kernel space.
[src:linux-kernel/monolithic-kernel] The monolithic model differs from other architectures such as the microkernel in that it alone defines a high-level virtual interface over computer hardware.
[src:linux-kernel/monolithic-kernel] A set of primitives or system calls implement all operating system services such as process management, concurrency, and memory management.
[src:linux-kernel/monolithic-kernel] Device drivers can be added to the kernel as loadable kernel modules.
[src:linux-kernel/monolithic-kernel] Modular operating systems such as OS-9 and most modern monolithic-kernel operating systems such as OpenVMS, Linux, FreeBSD, NetBSD, Solaris, and AIX can dynamically load (and unload) executable kernel modules at runtime.
[src:linux-kernel/monolithic-kernel] This modularity of the operating system is at the binary (image) level and not at the architecture level.
[src:linux-kernel/monolithic-kernel] Modular monolithic operating systems are not to be confused with the architectural level of modularity inherent in server-client operating systems (and its derivatives sometimes marketed as hybrid kernel) which use microkernels and servers (not to be mistaken for modules or daemons).
[src:linux-kernel/monolithic-kernel] Practically speaking, dynamically loading modules is simply a more flexible way of handling the operating system image at runtime—as opposed to rebooting with a different operating system image.
[src:linux-kernel/monolithic-kernel] The modules allow easy extension of the operating systems' capabilities as required.
[src:linux-kernel/monolithic-kernel] Dynamically loadable modules incur a small overhead when compared to building the module into the operating system image.
[src:linux-kernel/monolithic-kernel] However, in some cases, loading modules dynamically (as-needed) helps to keep the amount of code running in kernel space to a minimum; for example, to minimize operating system footprint for embedded devices or those with limited hardware resources.
[src:linux-kernel/monolithic-kernel] Namely, an unloaded module need not be stored in scarce random access memory.
[src:linux-kernel/procfs] Typically, it is mapped to a mount point named */proc* at boot time.
[src:linux-kernel/procfs] The proc file system acts as an interface to internal data structures about running processes in the kernel.
[src:linux-kernel/procfs] In Linux, it can also be used to obtain information about the kernel and to change certain kernel parameters at runtime (sysctl).
[src:linux-kernel/procfs] Many Unix-like operating systems support the proc filesystem, including System V, Solaris, IRIX, Tru64 UNIX, BSD, Linux, IBM AIX, QNX, and Plan 9 from Bell Labs.
[src:linux-kernel/procfs] OpenBSD dropped support in version 5.7, released in May 2015.
[src:linux-kernel/procfs] The Linux kernel extends it to non–process-related data.
[src:linux-kernel/procfs] The proc filesystem provides a method of communication between kernel space and user space.
[src:linux-kernel/procfs] For example, the ps command on Plan 9 and the GNU version of the process reporting utility ps uses the proc file system to obtain its data, without using any specialized system calls.
[src:linux-kernel/procfs] Killian implemented the UNIX 8th Edition (V8) version of */proc*: he presented a paper titled "Processes as Files" at USENIX in June 1984.
[src:linux-kernel/procfs] The design of procfs aimed to replace the *ptrace* system call used for process tracing.
[src:linux-kernel/procfs] Detailed documentation can be found in the proc(4) manual page.
[src:linux-kernel/procfs] The original AT&T System V Release 3 (SVR3) operating system (available internally to AT&T in 1986 and generally in 1987) did not come with the */proc* filesystem, but a subsequent incremental version of it did.
[src:linux-kernel/procfs] It only contained files representing the processes rather than the now common subdirectories.
[src:linux-kernel/procfs] Roger Faulkner and Ron Gomes ported V8 */proc* to SVR4, and published a paper called "The Process File System and Process Model in UNIX System V" at USENIX in January 1991.
[src:linux-kernel/procfs] This kind of procfs supported the creation of *ps*, but the files could only be accessed with functions *read()*, *write()*, and *ioctl()*.
[src:linux-kernel/procfs] Between 1995 and 1996, Roger Faulkner created the procfs-2 interface for Solaris-2.6 that offers a structured /proc filesystem with sub-directories.
[src:linux-kernel/procfs] Plan 9 implemented a process file system, but went further than V8.
[src:linux-kernel/procfs] V8's process file system implemented a single file per process.
[src:linux-kernel/procfs] Plan 9 created a hierarchy of separate files to provide those functions, and made /proc a real part of the file system.
[src:linux-kernel/procfs] Furthermore, Plan 9's approach to portability allows systems with different architectures and byte order to debug others' processes.
[src:linux-kernel/procfs] 4.4BSD cloned its implementation of /proc from Plan 9.
[src:linux-kernel/procfs] As of February 2011, procfs is gradually becoming phased out in FreeBSD, and it has turned to use the *sysctl* interface instead for process-related information.
[src:linux-kernel/procfs] To provide binary compatibility with Linux user space programs, the FreeBSD kernel also provides **linprocfs** that is similar to the Linux procfs.
[src:linux-kernel/procfs] It was removed from OpenBSD in version 5.7, which was released in May 2015, because it "always suffered from race conditions and is now unused". macOS did not implement procfs and user space programs have to use the *sysctl* interface for retrieving process data.
[src:linux-kernel/procfs] /proc in Solaris was available from the beginning (June 1992).
[src:linux-kernel/procfs] Solaris 2.6 in 1996 introduced procfs2 from Roger Faulkner.
[src:linux-kernel/procfs] Linux first added a /proc filesystem in v0.97.3, September 1992, and first began expanding it to non-process related data in v0.98.6, December 1992.
[src:linux-kernel/procfs] As of 2020, the Linux implementation includes a directory for each running process, including kernel processes, in directories named /proc/PID, where PID is the process number.
[src:linux-kernel/procfs] A CPU package means physical CPU which can have multiple cores (*single core* for one, *dual core* for two, *quad core* for four).
[src:linux-kernel/procfs] This allows a distinction between hyper-threading and dual-core, i.e. the number of hyper-threads per CPU package can be calculated by *siblings / CPU cores*.
[src:linux-kernel/procfs] If both values for a CPU package are the same, then hyper-threading is not supported.
[src:linux-kernel/procfs] For instance, a CPU package with siblings=2 and "cpu cores"=2 is a dual-core CPU but does not support hyper-threading.
[src:linux-kernel/procfs] The basic utilities that use /proc under Linux come in the procps (/proc processes) package, and only function in conjunction with a mounted /proc.
[src:linux-kernel/procfs] Cygwin implemented a procfs that is basically the same as the Linux procfs.
